result.execSummary:
The defendant Angel M Ceballos was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • 4th Degree Sexual Assault, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.225(3m).
  • Exposing Genitals/Pubic Area/Intimate Parts to a Child, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 948.10(1)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
Defendant Angel M Ceballos in court with attorney Jamie Francis Cimpl-Wiemer.  Defendant Angel M Ceballos in custody.  Jennifer Lynn Williams appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy Clerk;ds

Case heard for Br. 25.  Defense moves for adjournment.  Arguments by counsel.  Court denies motion to adjourn.  Sentencing proceeds.    Upon inquiry of the Court, State advises they have complied with victim notification. Statements by counsel, Joe R. and defendant.

Court advises the defendant he may not possess a firearm; is to provide a DNA sample and cannot vote until his civil rights are restored.  

Count 1: COURT ORDERS defendant to serve 9 months at the House of Correction with Huber for actual work and school and 88 days credit - defendant is eligible for the Inmate Work Release program; pay mandatory costs, assessments and surcharges by 7-1-16 or  a civil judgment is to be entered against the defendant and subject to other collection.

Court advises the defendant any possession or use of any illegally controlled substance or alcohol forfeits the release privileges. 

Count 2:  COURT ORDERS defendant to serve a term in the Wisconsin State Prison system - TOTAL LENGTH OF SENTENCE - 24 months - consecutive to Count 1; INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT - 12 months; EXTENDED SUPERVISION - 12 months.  COURT STAYS the sentence and places the defendant on probation for a period of 2  years - consecutive to Count 1.

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION:  1) no violations of the criminal law rising to the level of probable cause; 2) sex offender evaluation, treatment or program; 3) no contact with the victim or her family and cannot be within 500 feet of her residence, school or work; 4) no unsupervised contaceith with anyone under 17 years of age unless supervised by an adult - except with his sister; 5) cognitive intervention program; 6) pay mandatory costs, assessments and surcharges or a civil judgment is to be entered against the defendant; 7) seek and maintain employment.  

CONDITIONS OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION:  1) no violations of criminal law rising to the level of probable cause; 2) pay any monetary amounts ordered but not yet paid on Count 2; 3) sex offender treatment or evaluation; 4) seek and maintain employment; 5) no contact with victim or her family and cannot be within 500 feet of residence, school or work.

Court finds defendant is not eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program or the Substance abuse Program.

COURT ORDERS:
-  defendant to provide a specimen for DNA testing;
- defendant must comply with sex offender reporting requirements for 15 years;
- restitution set at -0-.

Appeal rights given.  Written Explanation of Determinate Sentence, Notice of Right to Seek Postconviction Relief, Pretrial Incarceration Credit and Ineligible Voting Notice & Acknowledgment received and filed.  Copies given to the defendant.  

As to Count 2:  Court finds the defendant was under the age of 25 at the time of the offense, the charge is a Class I felony, society would not be harmed and the defendant would benefit by expungement.  Court grants expungement upon successful completion of the sentence.

Defendant sworn in.

As to COUNT 1 as AMENDED and COUNT 2 as AMENDED-
Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, and plead GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights, Addendum, and Jury Instructions received and filed.  Stipulation by parties to the Criminal Complaint as a factual basis to sustain the plea.  Court found the defendant guilty.  Judgments of conviction entered.
  
Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess any gun or other firearms. 
Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended, and may not vote in any election until his civil rights are restored.  

Court advised defendant if he is not a citizen of the United States of America, that upon a plea of guilty or no contest for this offense, he could be deported, excluded from admission to his country, or denied naturalization under federal law.  
Court advised that the defendant will have to provide a DNA sample, to the Wisconsin State Crime Laboratory for DNA testing and pay a DNA surcharge.

Court advised the defendant of the sex offender registry requirements.

Court ordered the defendant REMANDED into custody. Court vacated the jury trial date of 7/13/15. Case adjourned to Branch 25. Sentencing hearing scheduled for July 15, 2015 at 08:30 am.
